I made this recipe and it was excellent, however for the non-vegi people in my house I ommitted a few things. Such as the carrot, bell pepper, and zucchini. I also substituted a can of plain tomatoe sauce instead of the crushed tomatoes, and the italian stewed tomatoes. It was still really a great meal his way but if you enjoy a more diverse chunky sauce I suggest leaving the vegis in.

Rating: 4
This has become a family favorite! I cook things in a different order though - particularly the sausage - I cook it first, dump it on several layers of paper towel to soak up the grease; pour any remianing grease out of the pan; lightly carmelize the onions and garlic in any remaining fat; add the mushrooms and wine to the pan and simmer together until the scraps come loose from the bottom of pan then I add the meat/onions/garlic/wine mushrooms to the tomatoes; saute the peppers and zucchini and add them to the tomatoes etc. and let it all simmer together for a bit. Wonderful! Freezes well too!

Rating: 0
not rating it, but i just wanted to say that i unwittingly made a sauce very similar to this, and it was excellent. i used celery instead of bell pepper (for a mirepoix), 2 tbsp tomato paste, dried basil and thyme w/ the oregano, and a smaller proportion of canned tomatoes. the key, for me, is simmering the mirepoix + garlic for a long time in the beginning, in plenty of oil, to really sweat it out (i think i cooked it for 1/2 hour). the sauce was delicious!

